Public procurement of works and prevention of corruption
Joint report by the Supreme Supervisory Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
Public procurement is important both for the government and for the economy.
The role of the State is to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
Public procurement in the European Union (EU) is an important element in creating a single economic area.
In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition across borders, contracting authorities have to comply with EU (threshold) standards.
To this end, EU member states must transpose and apply EU public procurement law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is left to individual countries to regulate public procurement themselves.
The awarding of benefits is also a corruption-prone area.
Due to the generally high potential for harm, contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and illegal favouritism in awarding their contracts.
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to carry out parallel audits for both EU-wide construction services and corruption prevention.
The audits focused on the application of EU public procurement legislation transposed into national legislation and the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in construction, road construction and transport infrastructure.
The sub-EU thresholds have also been considered with a view to preventing corruption.
The audit results of both courts of auditors are summarised in this Joint Report.
The report will also address international institutions such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
Audit areas and audited bodies The evaluations carried out by the Federal Court of Auditors on the issues listed are mainly based on cross-cutting audits carried out in 2011/2012 by the construction authorities responsible for road and high-rise construction in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major construction projects.
In addition, the Bundesrechnungshof drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Supervisory Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on examinations from 2008 to 2011.
