The foundations of EU public procurement law and corruption prevention
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted inter alia the Procurement Coordination and Remedies Directives, which were to be transposed into national law by the Member States.
The general principles of the European Union are, in particular, competition, equal treatment and non-discrimination and transparency.
To achieve these objectives, the procurement coordination directive contains specific provisions for construction works throughout the EU.
To do so, their expected order sums must reach or exceed 5,000,000 euros currently.
The rules relate in particular to the content of procurement documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the fulfilment of deadlines, inter alia for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that may be placed on the qualifications of applicants and the Remedies directive provides the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.
For possible infringements of public procurement law, companies can have their decisions reviewed in review procedures.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.
Prevention of corruption
Importance of corruption prevention
In both countries, there is no legal definition of the concept of corruption.
Corruption is generally understood as the abuse of a position of trust for private gain,
the latter is prompted by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5 percent of world output.
As far as the European Union is concerned, it is estimated that these costs will amount to one per cent.
For contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices can call into question trust in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.
They will have to review the organisation and sequencing of their administrations in particularly corruption-prone areas in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corrupt area of work.
