Results of the individual stages of the award procedure
Award documents
Procurement documents The award documents must contain all the information necessary for bidders to make an appropriate bid.
In particular, the award documents must allow for an accurate calculation.
Bidders must not be entrusted with risks that they cannot calculate.
The award documents consist in particular of the performance description and the terms of the contract.
They also contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders and the criteria for selecting the most economical bid.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law on public procurement documents relate in particular to technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.
In principle, the performance description must be product neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the performance description is only allowed under strict conditions.
Avoiding anti-competitive requirements in procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of corruption prevention.
Furthermore, unclear or incorrect information must be avoided in the award documents, as they provide scope for speculation in making the offers and for manipulation of their valuation.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Similar or similar rules Both countries have transposed the EU technical specifications requirements into national law.
The services are basically product neutral with no factory requirements to tender.
In the performance descriptions, the individual services must normally be divided in detail into performance units with respective quantities.
Prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. euro per m2 or per unit).
Only in exceptional cases may services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the performance descriptions must be complete and clear.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include benefits that do not determine whether they are needed.
Remuneration after a lump sum or after time must be avoided where possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on unspecified requirements in the award documents.
The performance descriptions must allow bidders to create their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The tender should not be made public until the award documents are finalised.
Different rules
There is no obligation to tender for works in lots in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of performance to be carried out, the public contracting bodies can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, works are generally divided into lots, separately by quantity (division) and/or type or subject area (expert).
This will allow SMEs to compete, increase the number of potential suppliers and make price fixing more difficult.
This type of award is considered the most usually economical.
Evaluation criteria must be specified in the Czech Republic for both EU and national procedures in the award documents.
This should allow applicants to fully and definitively identify the criteria for evaluating their offers.
In Germany, valuation criteria are required in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in procurement documents, only in EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria are only to be found in an administrative award notice.
Procurement documents prepared by contracted professionals may not contain references to these offices or involved planners or appraisers in Germany with the high-rise construction and some road construction administrations.
This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the knowledge of the client about contact with these professionals.
This is also why professionals are not allowed to send contracting documents or interpret planning documents for insight.
The company's contact person is the client alone.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services that prove necessary after the original contract is concluded (nights) almost always fall for large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow to a certain extent the award of night contracts to the already contracted company without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to EU and German rules, the remuneration of supplementary payments may not exceed half of the principal contract.
Furthermore, the additional benefits cannot be separated from the main mission without significant disadvantages or must be strictly necessary.
In the Czech Republic, an award without public notice is subject to a narrower limit of 20 percent.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.
If supplementary payments are transferred to the already contracted company, the rules in Germany do not allow an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor.
The calculation of the remuneration for the additional services is based on the agreed prices and the basis for the price determination of the contract already awarded.
As well as supplements, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
Minor quantities cannot be offset with additional supplements in the Czech Republic.
