Setting the method of award and taking into account the EU threshold
By determining the method of award, the contracting authority determines the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential applicants and bidders largely unrestricted, for example by choosing an open procedure, or by requiring non-public procurement procedures.
Construction projects that meet or exceed a threshold set by the EU are subject to pan-European tendering procedures.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
When choosing the method of award, the contracting authority must take account in particular of the European rules on competition and transparency.
If the total estimated contract value of a project's construction is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5,000,000 euros, construction services must in principle be awarded on an open or non-open basis throughout Europe.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
For construction projects reaching or exceeding the EU threshold, the contracting authority may derogate to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European procurement and award construction services in national contracts, provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than EUR 1,000,000 and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20 per cent of the estimated total contract value of all construction contracts.
A single construction project cannot be divided into individual measures without compelling reason or deliberately valued at too low a cost to escape the obligation to award construction services across Europe.
Because restrictions on competition greatly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of method of award is important in preventing corruption.
The detailed justification of the chosen method and the assessment of the application of EU public procurement rules are important elements in the documentation of the award procedure.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully implemented EU public procurement and threshold requirements into national law.
Different rules
The Czech Republic has also transferred the basic equivalence of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU Directive to its construction contracts which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the unopened procedure, without the choice of doku mentoring or justifying, whereas other procedures are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, however, the open procedure or, in the case of national procurement, public procurement is a matter of principle.
Other types of procurement, such as the non-open procedure or the restricted tendering procedure, are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated by public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be clearly justified and documented.
The principle of primacy of the open procedure/public tender is intended to ensure the most unrestricted competition, to avoid manipulation by targeting specific bidders and to complicate possible price fixing among bidders.
The principle of public procurement is a central element of corruption prevention in Germany.
The true estimate of the expected contract value is an essential basis in choosing the right method of award.
Construction services in Germany can rely on planning and cost databases of public administrations and other organisations to determine the likely cost of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects, including cost benchmarks for building categories, utility units, components or individual construction services.
Based on such cost metrics, the expected contract value of a planned pre-bens or construction performance can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction have only some construction administrations in Germany.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road-building administrations is provided.
Awarding bodies in the Czech Republic cannot use central databases or average price calculations of comparable construction in calculating the estimated cost of construction services.
Cost assessments are mostly based on estimates by the financing body or on the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures to standardise cost assessment procedures are still in their early stages.
