Key exam results BRH
Choice of the award procedure
The contracting authorities audited the works largely by open procedure or public tender, thereby complying with budgetary and public procurement requirements.
In 2011, 59.5 percent of federal construction in high-rise construction was put out to public or open tender.
In the road sector, this figure was 94.8 per cent.
The selection of non-public tenderers lacked in part detailed justifications as to why awarding bodies had to deviate from the principle of open tender.
In a cross-cutting investigation, the BRH found, based on more than 16,000 procurement procedures, that the non-public procurement types have significant competitive disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation and corruption.
In high construction, more than twice as many tenders were submitted to public tenders as to restricted tenders and nearly three times as many offers as to free-handed contracts.
The investigation also showed that bid prices for restricted tenders and open-ended tenders were, on average, 6 percent and 10 percent higher respectively than for public tenders.
Parallel research by the Federal Ministry of Buildings and a National Audit Office confirmed the cost-effectiveness differences between public and non-public procurement types.
The federal construction ministry even came up with twice the difference between public and non-public procurement procedures as a result of its investigations into cost-effectiveness.
