Review and evaluation of the bids
Review and evaluation of offers The client shall examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.
In doing so, it must determine the offer for awarding the contract that best meets the requirements according to the specified award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The EU rules provide for a step-by-step approach:
First, the suitability of the bidders is established.
Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
The principle of exclusion from the award procedure is that companies with final convictions for, for example, bribery or fraud are excluded.
The offers of the non-excluded bidders are to be examined computationally, technically and economically and assessed on the basis of previously disclosed award criteria.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer.
The examination and evaluation of the bids is a particularly sensitive phase of the tendering process.
For example, bidders can be unfairly excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can be left to compete.
The advantages or disadvantages of bidders may unduly affect the valuation result and thus prevent the finding of the most economically advantageous tender.
The contracting authority must therefore take special measures to ensure that the persons charged with the examination and evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure that the procedure and the decisions taken are transparent and comprehensible.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar arrangements
In line with EU requirements, offers in both countries will have to be assessed and evaluated in several stages.
Requirements for companies' qualifications to be presented and the award criteria to be taken into account during evaluation and their weighting are laid down in the notices or the award documents and cannot be modified during the procedure.
After testing the bidding event, the suitability criteria may no longer be used in evaluating the offers.
The rating must be limited to the award criteria.
The bids submitted must be formally examined immediately to see whether they are complete and whether they contain, for example, any evidence of possible manipulation.
If bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their offers, they must be informed immediately.
