The decisions taken in the examination and evaluation of the offers must be documented.
Different rules
In Germany, the secret offers may only be made available to those directly charged with processing them.
The inspection of tenders and the computational examination of tenders can only be carried out by the contracting authority.
It shall only employ officials not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of the other audit and evaluation tasks is not specified.
If professionals are entrusted with the examination and evaluation, they must keep the offers confidential.
They may only make proposals for the decisions to be taken by the awarding bodies.
In the Czech Republic, award committees are to be set up to examine and evaluate the bids.
The committees prepare evaluation reports with award proposals.
Ultimately, as in Germany, procurement is decided only by the awarding bodies.
Where evidence or declarations requested for tender in Germany are incomplete, the contracting authority must allow bidders to recover the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the deadline can the offer be excluded.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the awarding body whether it gives bidders the opportunity to complete missing evidence or explanations.
If a bidder fails to do so, he must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers must be examined.
If the price structure of the offer indicates that the prices for partial services are too low or too high, the bidder must be asked to remove these ambiguities.
If it fails to do so and the contracting authority can provide proof of a mixed price calculation, this offer shall be excluded.
This is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant volume changes in partial services when calculating their offer, allowing significant cost increases in construction projects.
In the Czech Republic the total price is assessed but not the adequacy of prices for partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
A surcharge may not be awarded in Germany for offers with unreasonably high or low prices.
If one or more offers the correct price determination of the client or the bid sums of the other bidders by 10 percent or more, the bidders will have to prove the proper calcula tion of their offers.
