Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention by documenting procurement procedures are implemented a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency imperative.
Documentation prepared carefully and in a timely manner only makes the award decisions traceable.
In particular, it also ensures effective legal protection for bidders when awarding contracts above EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, because forcing award decisions to be thoroughly justified substantially reduces room for manipulation.
The notification of a contract awarded in an EU-wide award procedure is to be sent to the EU Publications Office within 48 days.
The Office also implements the transparency requirement in the Official Journal of the EU.
The contracting authorities must also collect the essential data from their procurement procedures and report it to the EU Commission through the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the Commission produces an annual EU statistical survey of the development of the internal market in construction services.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully transposed EU documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The arrangements for documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Different rules
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish awarded contracts is not limited to EU-wide procurement but also extends to other procurement procedures.
The notice period is shortened to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to EU-wide procurement, there is only an obligation to publish only limited tenders and free-handed contracts above value limits of 25,000 euros and 15,000 euros without sales tax.
Below these thresholds and in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure will be informed about the award of contracts.
Key exam results
BRH
Documentation
A large number of the tender procedures examined were not fully documented.
The notices did not contain all the necessary information, such as justification of product requirements or references to national regulations.
In an award procedure, the contracting authority did not justify the awarding of the contract to a company, even though its offer did not contain compelling evidence.
In a few cases, the documents of the awarding bodies did not contain all the evidence necessary to document the award procedure.
Notices on placing orders
In some EU-wide procurement procedures, awarding bodies failed to disclose the award of the contracts.
Further procurement procedures lacked evidence that the awarding bodies had disclosed the contracts awarded.
Reporting and reporting obligations
The statistical data included the required minimum information.
Ex-post transparency
The audited building administrations published in most cases the contract data of the completed procurement procedures.
However, a construction administration did not publish this data because of a transmission error.
The building administration only noticed this error after six months,
so that the contract details of the procurement procedures completed by then have not been published.
