Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of NK and BRH have focused on two main areas essential for public procurement in the Czech Republic and Germany: the application of EU public procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
EU law provides for cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Anti-corruption measures are designed not only to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of the public procurement rules in both countries and their comparison reveal commonalities and differences that can help both countries to develop and apply their procurement law.
Application of EU public procurement rules
Both countries have transposed the EU requirements on the award of construction services into national law.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for awarding works and taking into account the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the undertakings involved and transparency of procurement procedures.
Construction administrations in both countries have, in some cases, backed up these bids very extensively with other administrative regulations.
The Czech Republic has also largely transferred the requirements for EU-wide construction services to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, investigations by the Court of Auditors have shown that building authorities have not fully complied with EU law in all areas.
Construction management in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to address the concerns raised when implementing EU requirements.
The audits in the Czech Republic showed in particular risks affecting the efficiency of the awards.
For example, incomplete performance descriptions required additional services, often provided in violation of legislation, and cost assessments were often inadequate; excessive qualification requirements reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, especially in transport buildings.
Prevention of corruption
The investigations have not aimed to uncover corruption cases,
also because the Court of Auditors does not have the appropriate instruments.
However, the courts of auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of construction services and how these guidelines are applied.
Both countries have different priorities in preventing corruption.
In particular, the German rules provide for largely unrestricted competition and transparency and controls as key elements in the prevention of corruption.
The main aim of the Czech rules is to increase the transparency of procedures.
BRH
General principles of corruption prevention apply in Germany.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of works and their specific needs.
Some of the rules specify very precisely how bids for the prevention of corruption should be taken into account in the course of procurement procedures and in the selection of persons involved.
In particular, the BRH considers that the primacy of the open procedure principle or public tendering is an appropriate tool to substantially reduce the risk of corruption in the award of construction services.
Risk analyses and sufficient controls (especially the multi-eye principle), transparency and documentation requirements and various organisational measures are also effective safeguards to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The BRH therefore sees no need for fundamental changes to the relevant requirements of administrations in the award of works.
The rules on corruption prevention are largely taken into account in practice.
The deficiencies found in some areas highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some benchmarks.
Building administrations should further train and raise awareness on corruption prevention.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building administrations had delegated to freelancers.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, delegating tasks increases the risk of abuse.
Manipulation and corruption-prone tasks should therefore be entrusted to third parties only if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against improper interference.
nkx
The Czech Republic adopted at government level an anti-corruption strategy.
The procurement law and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The audits of the NKx took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures as awarding bodies must justify the economics of contract awards, the calculation of expected prices, the adequacy of qualification requirements, the essential assessment criteria and the nature of assessments, and properly document and publish all of these aspects.
Recommendations
The NK and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU requirements.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU rules on competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for awarding works within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects to enable and promote cross-border competition.
Given the huge material and ideal potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see calls for their countries' building administrations to continue and possibly improve their actions against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and take appropriate countermeasures.
Comparing procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open cases should be increased in the Czech Republic, as open procedures can provide wider scope for competition and substantially reduce the risk of corruption.
Also, greater sharing of construction services in lots can have a favourable impact on bid prices, provided it leads to greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient procurement by public authorities.
In Germany, procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised construction authorities, whereas in the Czech Republic, with the exception of transport projects, these tasks are carried out by the departments themselves or contractors appointed by them.
The Courts of Auditors of both countries are committed to developing their respective knowledge and, where appropriate, bringing it to the parliament and government of their country.
Both audit bodies also believe that the principles of procurement law set out in this report and its implementation at the international level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI) are of interest, because the principles and findings set out are of general importance to counter corruption effectively and to ensure the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
